''Ultima IV'' was the top game on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s list of software best sellers for February and March 1986.<ref name="compute198606">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1986-06-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_073_1986_Jun#page/n101/mode/2up | title=Hotware: Software Best Sellers | work=Compute! | date=June 1986 | access-date=8 November 2013 | pages=102}}</ref>  In the United States, ''Ultima IV'' had sold more than 100,000 copies by August 1986.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Petska-Juliussen |first1=Karen |last2=Juliussen |first2=Egil |title=The Computer Industry Almanac 1990 |date=1990 |publisher=Brady |isbn=978-0-13-154122-1 |location=New York |pages=3.12 |url=https://archive.org/details/computerindustry00kare/page/n267/mode/2up}}</ref> Global sales of ''Ultima IV'' had surpassed 400,000 copies by May 1989.<ref name="gamesmachinesales">{{cite magazine |author=Staff |magazine=[[The Games Machine]] |title=Controversy; Hold the Front Page! |date=18 May 1989 |issue=19 (June 1989) |page=100 |url=https://archive.org/details/thegamesmachine-19/page/n99}}</ref>

[[Scorpia (journalist)|Scorpia]] of ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' in 1986 called it "an incredible game", only criticizing the fact that experience only came from combat, which she stated became "tedious". Scorpia concluded, "What are you waiting for? This will be a classic... go get it!!"<ref name="scorpia198602">{{cite magazine |title=Ultima IV: Quest of the Avatar |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=January–February 1986 |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1986&pub=2&id=25 |access-date=1 November 2013 |author=Scorpia |pages=12}}</ref> The game became the first to replace ''[[Wizardry: Proving Grounds of the Mad Overlord]]''—the top-rated adventure game for five years—in the magazine's reader poll,<ref name="cgw198604">{{cite magazine |title=Reader Input Device |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=April 1986 |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1986&pub=2&id=27 |access-date=1 November 2013 |pages=48}}</ref> and it named ''Ultima IV'' as the game of the year for 1986.<ref name="cgw198712">{{cite magazine |title=Computer Gaming World Meets Dragoncon '87 |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=December 1987 |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1987&pub=2&id=42 |access-date=2 November 2013 |pages=22}}</ref> In 1987 Scorpia cited ''Ultima IV'' for taking the genre away from hack and slash—"for the first time, we have a CRPG whose focus IS character development. Not how many monsters you kill, nor how much loot you can pick up"<ref name="scorpia198707">{{cite magazine |title=Computer Role-Playing Games / Now and Beyond |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=June–July 1987 |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1987&pub=2&id=38 |access-date=2 November 2013 |author=Scorpia |author-link=Scorpia (journalist) |pages=28}}</ref>—in 1991 and 1993 called it her favorite game,<ref name="scorpia199110">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1991&pub=2&id=87 |title=C*R*P*G*S / Computer Role-Playing Game Survey |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=October 1991 |access-date=18 November 2013 |author=Scorpia |pages=16}}</ref><ref name="scorpia199310">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1993&pub=2&id=111 |title=Scorpia's Magic Scroll Of Games |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=October 1993 |access-date=25 March 2016 |author=Scorpia |pages=34–50}}</ref> in 1994 stated that "maybe nothing ever will" surpass it,<ref name="scorpia199408">{{Cite magazine |author=Scorpia |date=August 1994 |title=Scorpia The Avatar |department=Scorpia's Sting |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1994&pub=2&id=121 |magazine=Computer Gaming World |pages=29–33 }}</ref> and after retiring from reviewing games called it "my all-time, number one, favorite RPG".<ref name="bellaonline">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bellaonline.com/articles/art8555.asp |title=Scorpia : A Pioneer in Computer Gaming |last=Shea |first=Lisa |website=BellaOnline}}</ref>

In June 1986, ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]''{{'}}s Hartley and Pattie Lesser called ''Ultima IV'' "The most impressive and complex adventure to date; a total adventuring environment that takes place across an entire continent."<ref name="Dragon110">{{cite journal|title=The Role of Computers|last1=Lesser|first1=Hartley |first2=Pattie|last2=Lesser|journal=[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]|issue=110|date=June 1986|pages=38–43}}</ref> In the September 1986 issue, [[Michael Gray (game designer)|Mike Gray]] lauded the game as "the best computer simulation of a true fantasy role-playing experience I have ever seen. If you have an Apple II or a Commodore 64 or 128, your treasure hoard of computer FRP games will not be complete unless and until you get your hands on this one". He praised ''Ultima IV'' as "incredible. If you can find it in a store, don’t pass it up... Don’t be discouraged if it takes you a while to find a copy — that search will be an easy one compared to what awaits you when you start the Quest of the Avatar".<ref name=dragon>{{cite journal|last=Gray|first=Mike| date=September 1986 |title=The Dragon's Augury|journal=[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]|publisher=[[TSR (company)|TSR, Inc.]]|issue=113|pages=41}}</ref>

''[[Famitsu]]'' reviewed the [[Famicom]] (NES) version and scored it 31 out of 40.<ref name="Fam"/> ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' magazine reviewed the Sega Master System version in 1990, giving it an 89% score.<ref name="CVG"/>

Co-creator of ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]'' [[Dave Arneson]] in 1988 wrote that ''Ultima IV'' and a few other games "have stood pretty much alone as quirks instead of trend setters" in the CRPG industry, as other games did not follow their innovations.<ref name="arneson198805">{{cite magazine | title=The Future of Computer Role-Playing | magazine=Computer Gaming World | date=May 1988 | access-date=3 November 2013 | author=Arneson, David L. | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1988&pub=2&id=47 | pages=24}}</ref>

With a score of 7.80 out of 10, in 1988 ''Ultima IV'' was among the first members of the ''Computer Gaming World'' Hall of Fame for those games rated highly over time by readers.<ref name="cgw198803">{{cite magazine | title=The CGW Hall of Fame | magazine=Computer Gaming World | date=March 1988 | access-date=2 November 2013 | pages=44 | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1988&pub=2&id=45}}</ref> In 1990 the game received the third-highest number of votes in a survey of readers' "All-Time Favorites".<ref name="cgw199001">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1990&pub=2&id=67 | title=CGW Readers Select All-Time Favorites | magazine=Computer Gaming World | date=January 1990 | access-date=15 November 2013 | pages=64}}</ref> In 1996, the magazine ranked it as the second-best video game of all time,<ref name="cgw199611best">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | title=150 Best Games of All Time | magazine=Computer Gaming World | date=November 1996 | access-date=25 March 2016 | pages=64–80}}</ref> and the second most-innovative computer game.<ref name="cgw199611innovative">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | title=The 15 Most Innovative Computer Games | magazine=Computer Gaming World | date=November 1996 | access-date=25 March 2016 | pages=102}}</ref> In 2013, ''[[IGN]]'' placed ''Ultima IV'' at #26 in its list of top 100 RPGs of all time.<ref name=igntop>{{citation | url=http://www.ign.com/top/rpgs | title=Top 100 RPGs of All Time | year=2013 | access-date=1 November 2013 | journal=[[IGN]] | archive-date=2 May 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502211325/http://www.ign.com/top/rpgs | url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2015, Peter Tieryas of ''[[Tor.com]]'' stated that the NES version "represented a different type of ideal... You make up the narrative and you determine the course of your journey, engendering a sense of immersion that had the effect of making you feel like you were in more control than any previous RPG."<ref name="tor.com">{{cite news | url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2015/03/whats-the-point-of-an-rpg-without-a-main-villain-how-ultima-iv-changed-the-game |  title=What's the Point of an RPG Without a Main Villain? How Ultima IV Changed the Game | work=Tor.com | date=March 2015 | author=Tieryas, Peter.}}</ref>

